## Philanthropic Contributions

### Scale and Scope of Philanthropy

After retiring from active business in the mid-1890s, Rockefeller devoted himself to philanthropy, donating over $530 million (equivalent to billions today) to various causes throughout his life ([The New York Times, 1937](https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/98/05/17/specials/rockefeller-gifts.html)). His philanthropic approach was methodical and scientific, aiming to create lasting impact rather than temporary relief.

### Major Foundations and Institutions

Rockefeller established several key institutions to manage and direct his charitable efforts:

| Foundation/Institution              | Purpose and Impact                                                                                  |
|-----------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Rockefeller Foundation (1913)     | Promoted global well-being through education, scientific research, public health, and the humanities. Funded medical research and social sciences worldwide ([The New York Times, 1937](https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/98/05/17/specials/rockefeller-gifts.html)). |
| Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research | Advanced medical science, now known as Rockefeller University, a leading biomedical research center. |
| General Education Board           | Supported education initiatives across the United States, particularly in the South, improving public schooling and higher education. |
| Laura Spelman Rockefeller Memorial | Established in memory of his wife, focused on social welfare and education.                       |
| University of Chicago             | Founded and endowed by Rockefeller, becoming a premier institution of higher learning.             |

### Areas of Focus

Rockefeller's philanthropy primarily targeted:

- **Education:** Funding schools, universities, and educational boards to improve access and quality.
- **Scientific Research:** Supporting medical and natural sciences to advance knowledge and public health.
- **Religious and Social Organizations:** Including Baptist institutions and the YMCA.
- **Social Reform Movements:** Notably, he contributed over $500,000 to the Anti-Saloon League, which was instrumental in the passage of Prohibition ([The New York Times, 1937](https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/98/05/17/specials/rockefeller-gifts.html)).

### Impact of Philanthropy

Rockefeller's philanthropic legacy has had enduring effects:

- Enabled breakthroughs in medical research, improving health outcomes globally.
- Elevated educational standards and accessibility, particularly in underserved regions.
- Supported social reforms that shaped American society in the early 20th century.
- Demonstrated a model of "scientific giving," emphasizing efficiency and sustainability in charity.

